The Bharatiya Nyaya Sanhita, 2023 defines "punishments" for offenders under Section 4. According to this section, the punishments to which offenders are liable under the provisions of the Sanhita include:

(a) Death;
(b) Imprisonment for life;
(c) Imprisonment, which is of two descriptions: 
   (1) Rigorous, that is, with hard labour;
   (2) Simple;
(d) Forfeiture of property;
(e) Fine;
(f) Community Service.

These categories outline the various forms of punishment that can be imposed on offenders as per the legal framework established by the Sanhita.

The right of private defence of property extends to causing death under the conditions specified in Section 41 of the provided legal text. According to this section, the right of private defence of property allows for the voluntary causing of death or any other harm to the wrong-doer if the offence, which occasions the exercise of the right, falls under any of the following descriptions:

(a) Robbery;
(b) House-breaking after sunset and before sunrise;
(c) Mischief by fire or any explosive substance committed on any building, tent, or vessel, which is used as a human dwelling or as a place for the custody of property;
(d) Theft, mischief, or house-trespass, under circumstances that may reasonably cause apprehension that death or grievous hurt will be the consequence if the right of private defence is not exercised.

These conditions are subject to the restrictions specified in Section 37, which generally limit the right of private defence to actions necessary for the purpose of defence and prohibit inflicting more harm than necessary.

In the context of criminal law, as outlined in the provided text, "force" is defined as an action where a person causes motion, change of motion, or cessation of motion to another person. This can also include causing any substance to come into contact with any part of another person's body, or with anything that person is wearing or carrying, or with anything so situated that such contact affects that person's sense of feeling. The definition specifies that the person causing the motion, change of motion, or cessation of motion must do so in one of the following ways:

(a) By their own bodily power;
(b) By disposing any substance in such a manner that the motion, change, or cessation of motion takes place without any further act on their part, or on the part of any other person;
(c) By inducing any animal to move, change its motion, or cease to move.

This definition is crucial in understanding the application of "force" in various criminal acts, such as assault or criminal force, where the intent and manner of applying force are significant factors in determining the nature of the offense.

The actions considered as "trafficking of person" are outlined in section 143 of the provided legal documentation. Trafficking involves the recruitment, transportation, harboring, transfer, or receipt of a person or persons for the purpose of exploitation by means of:

(a) Using threats;
(b) Using force or any other form of coercion;
(c) Abduction;
(d) Practicing fraud or deception;
(e) Abuse of power;
(f) Inducement, including giving or receiving payments or benefits to achieve the consent of a person having control over the person being trafficked.

The term "exploitation" includes acts of physical or sexual exploitation, slavery or practices similar to slavery, servitude, beggary, or forced removal of organs. The consent of the victim is immaterial in determining the offence of trafficking.

The associated penalties for trafficking are as follows:

1. General trafficking: Rigorous imprisonment for a term not less than seven years, which may extend to ten years, and a fine.
2. Trafficking of more than one person: Rigorous imprisonment for a term not less than ten years, which may extend to life imprisonment, and a fine.
3. Trafficking of a child: Rigorous imprisonment for a term not less than ten years, which may extend to life imprisonment, and a fine.
4. Trafficking of more than one child: Rigorous imprisonment for a term not less than fourteen years, which may extend to life imprisonment, and a fine.
5. Repeat offender in trafficking of a child: Imprisonment for life, meaning imprisonment for the remainder of the person's natural life, and a fine.
6. Involvement of a public servant or police officer in trafficking: Imprisonment for life, meaning imprisonment for the remainder of the person's natural life, and a fine.
